{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "According to Clark and other supporters of HEC, cases like these only exemplify a much more widely realised feature of cognition.",
    "They claim, in a term popularized by Risko & Gilbert (2016), that cognizers like us characteristically offload cognition from their brains onto their bodily and environmental context.",
    "The supportive environments described by Clark offer multiple opportunities for offloading, but so do many more familiar tools and artefacts.",
    "For example, the bartender mentioned above engages in offloading when she arranges her workspace to more easily and reliably locate the ingredients she needs (Clark, 2008).",
    "Or consider someone writing out a long-division problem with a pen and paper."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "They claim, in a term popularized by Risko & Gilbert (2016), that cognizers like us characteristically offload cognition from their brains onto their bodily and environmental context.",
    "For example, the bartender mentioned above engages in offloading when she arranges her workspace to more easily and reliably locate the ingredients she needs (Clark, 2008)."
  ]
}